text.tspan: 4.19.5PROCESSING APPRAISALSAppraisals are uploaded into the PHOENIX database and are visible to all concerned staff in Head office and in manning offices andby manning agents for applicable crew membersThe appraisals are used as part of the selection and assignment process.4.19.6EVALUATION OF APPRAISALSAppraisals are to be reviewed by the crew department when the crew member is being evaluated for re-employment. At the sametime any identified "Training Needs" must also be addressed.If an appraisal is not available or in case of an adverse appraisal, waiver is required for the candidate to be re-employed.Authorities for granting waivers are as follows:Officers - General Manager.Ratings - Technical / Marine Superintendent and above.Secondary Approval Authorities are as follows:Officers - General Manager.Ratings - Technical / Marine Superintendent and above.4.19.7TIME FOR EVALUATIONIf the evaluation report of particular crewmembers cannot be made properly, depending on the embarkation and disembarkation timingof Master, department head or crewmembers, the period shall be so adjusted that the crewmembers are evaluated at least onceduring their tenure on the ship.4.19.8EVALUATION OF COMPETENCY AND FOLLOW-UP IN CASE OF INCOMPETENT CREW MEMBERSRefer to HSEQA Manual Section 15.2.34.19.9RETENTION OF RECORDSRecords of appraisals/ evaluations shall be maintained ashore in the PHOENIX system. Copies of evaluation records will be not bemaintained on board.4.20CREW TRAINING4.20.1TRAINING POLICYThe company provides initial and refresher training for all ranks. Training programs are based on identified needs and are over andabove the minimum STCW requirements and from Management’s desire for increased development of staff.The company determines additional training that is considered necessary to enhance safety and environmental performance levels.Provision of such training may arise from one or more of the following:· Internal and external audits that identify such needs· Incidents occurring on board indicating training requirements· Results of inspections, internal or by Third Party. · Training needs identified in appraisal reports/ drills on board· Management Reviews· From Management of Change (MOC) processes such as: a) New Regulations b) New Equipment c) Commencement of new activities or d) Acquisition of new ships e) Changes in Policies and proceduresSuch training may include both onboard and shore based training and consists of theoretical and practical parts.Effectiveness of Training is verified by the following means: · monthly fleet wide campaigns · Evaluations at the end of Training courses · Appraisals · Audits and Inspections4.20.2RESPONSIBILITIES
